00287 /* The following macros and typedefs allow an ASN1_ITEM
00288  * to be embedded in a structure and referenced. Since
00289  * the ASN1_ITEM pointers need to be globally accessible
00290  * (possibly from shared libraries) they may exist in
00291  * different forms. On platforms that support it the
00292  * ASN1_ITEM structure itself will be globally exported.
00293  * Other platforms will export a function that returns
00294  * an ASN1_ITEM pointer.
00295  *
00296  * To handle both cases transparently the macros below
00297  * should be used instead of hard coding an ASN1_ITEM
00298  * pointer in a structure.
00299  *
00300  * The structure will look like this:
00301  *
00302  * typedef struct SOMETHING_st {
00303  *      ...
00304  *      ASN1_ITEM_EXP *iptr;
00305  *      ...
00306  * } SOMETHING; 
00307  *
00308  * It would be initialised as e.g.:
00309  *
00310  * SOMETHING somevar = {...,ASN1_ITEM_ref(X509),...};
00311  *
00312  * and the actual pointer extracted with:
00313  *
00314  * const ASN1_ITEM *it = ASN1_ITEM_ptr(somevar.iptr);
00315  *
00316  * Finally an ASN1_ITEM pointer can be extracted from an
00317  * appropriate reference with: ASN1_ITEM_rptr(X509). This
00318  * would be used when a function takes an ASN1_ITEM * argument.
00319  *
00320  */
00321 
00322 #ifndef OPENSSL_EXPORT_VAR_AS_FUNCTION
00323 
00324 /* ASN1_ITEM pointer exported type */
00325 typedef const ASN1_ITEM ASN1_ITEM_EXP;
00326 
00327 /* Macro to obtain ASN1_ITEM pointer from exported type */
00328 #define ASN1_ITEM_ptr(iptr) (iptr)
00329 
00330 /* Macro to include ASN1_ITEM pointer from base type */
00331 #define ASN1_ITEM_ref(iptr) (&(iptr##_it))
00332 
00333 #define ASN1_ITEM_rptr(ref) (&(ref##_it))
00334 
00335 #define DECLARE_ASN1_ITEM(name) \
00336     OPENSSL_EXTERN const ASN1_ITEM name##_it;
00337 
00338 #else
00339 
00340 /* Platforms that can't easily handle shared global variables are declared
00341  * as functions returning ASN1_ITEM pointers.
00342  */
00343 
00344 /* ASN1_ITEM pointer exported type */
00345 typedef const ASN1_ITEM * ASN1_ITEM_EXP(void);
00346 
00347 /* Macro to obtain ASN1_ITEM pointer from exported type */
00348 #define ASN1_ITEM_ptr(iptr) (iptr())
00349 
00350 /* Macro to include ASN1_ITEM pointer from base type */
00351 #define ASN1_ITEM_ref(iptr) (iptr##_it)
00352 
00353 #define ASN1_ITEM_rptr(ref) (ref##_it())
00354 
00355 #define DECLARE_ASN1_ITEM(name) \
00356     const ASN1_ITEM * name##_it(void);

00384 /* Character needs escaping if it is the first character */
00385 #define CHARTYPE_FIRST_ESC_2253     0x20
00386 /* Character needs escaping if it is the last character */
00387 #define CHARTYPE_LAST_ESC_2253      0x40

00393 /* If this is set we convert all character strings
00394  * to UTF8 first 
00395  */

00399 /* If this is set we don't attempt to interpret content:
00400  * just assume all strings are 1 byte per character. This
00401  * will produce some pretty odd looking output!
00402  */
00403 
00404 #define ASN1_STRFLGS_IGNORE_TYPE    0x20
00405 
00406 /* If this is set we include the string type in the output */
00407 #define ASN1_STRFLGS_SHOW_TYPE      0x40
00408 
00409 /* This determines which strings to display and which to
00410  * 'dump' (hex dump of content octets or DER encoding). We can
00411  * only dump non character strings or everything. If we
00412  * don't dump 'unknown' they are interpreted as character
00413  * strings with 1 octet per character and are subject to
00414  * the usual escaping options.
00415  */
00416 
00417 #define ASN1_STRFLGS_DUMP_ALL       0x80
00418 #define ASN1_STRFLGS_DUMP_UNKNOWN   0x100
00419 
00420 /* These determine what 'dumping' does, we can dump the
00421  * content octets or the DER encoding: both use the
00422  * RFC2253 #XXXXX notation.
00423  */
00424 
00425 #define ASN1_STRFLGS_DUMP_DER       0x200

00428  * escaping control characters isn't essential in
00429  * RFC2253 but it is advisable anyway.
00430  */

00433                 ASN1_STRFLGS_ESC_CTRL | \
00434                 ASN1_STRFLGS_ESC_MSB | \
00435                 ASN1_STRFLGS_UTF8_CONVERT | \

00437                 ASN1_STRFLGS_DUMP_DER)
